<body><div class=WordSection1>
<div class="brand">📚 ENGLISH CODING · 영어코딩</div>
<h1>⚡ WD002 Week 1 — English Worksheet</h1>
<p><strong>Topic:</strong> Meeting JavaScript — <code>console.log</code> and <code>alert</code> · <strong>Course:</strong> Web Dev Basics: JavaScript · <strong>Time:</strong> about 45 minutes</p>
<p>This week you make a page <strong>move</strong> for the first time. HTML is the structure, CSS is the look, and <strong>JavaScript is the motion</strong>. You will use <code>console.log()</code> to send a message to the console, <code>alert()</code> to pop a message at the user, and a button to run your code when it is clicked.</p>
<hr />
<h2>1 · Predict 🔮</h2>
<p>Read each piece of code. Before you run it, write what you think will happen.</p>
<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;script&gt;
  console.log(&quot;Hello console&quot;);
  alert(&quot;Hello user&quot;);
&lt;/script&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Two messages appear in two different places. Where does each one show up?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;button onclick=&quot;sayHi()&quot;&gt;Click Me&lt;/button&gt;

&lt;script&gt;
  function sayHi() {
    alert(&quot;Hi there!&quot;);
  }
&lt;/script&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>When does the alert pop up — the moment the page loads, or later? What makes it run?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;script&gt;
  console.log(&quot;one&quot;);
  console.log(&quot;two&quot;);
  console.log(&quot;three&quot;);
&lt;/script&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>In what order do the three messages reach the console?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;button onclick=&quot;greet()&quot;&gt;Greet&lt;/button&gt;

&lt;script&gt;
  function greet() {
    console.log(&quot;greeting...&quot;);
    alert(&quot;Welcome!&quot;);
  }
&lt;/script&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>The button is clicked once. How many things happen, and in what order?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>2 · Spot the Bug 🐛</h2>
<p>Each block was meant to do something, but it is broken. Read what it is <strong>supposed</strong> to do, then rewrite it so it works. After that, explain why the original was wrong and why your fix works.</p>
<p><strong>Bug A</strong> — Clicking the button should pop an alert that says <code>Hello!</code>. Right now nothing happens when you click.</p>
<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;button onclick=&quot;sayHello()&quot;&gt;Click&lt;/button&gt;

&lt;script&gt;
  function sayhello() {
    alert(&quot;Hello!&quot;);
  }
&lt;/script&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> the button calls one name; the function is spelled another way. JavaScript is picky about capital letters.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug B</strong> — This should show a popup that says <code>Good job</code>. Right now the page shows an error.</p>
<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;script&gt;
  alert(Good job);
&lt;/script&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> text inside <code>alert()</code> needs something around it.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug C</strong> — Clicking should print <code>clicked</code> to the console. Right now the button does nothing.</p>
<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;button&gt;Press&lt;/button&gt;

&lt;script&gt;
  function reportClick() {
    console.log(&quot;clicked&quot;);
  }
&lt;/script&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> the function exists, but nothing ever calls it. How does the button know which function to run?</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>3 · Make It Yours 📸</h2>
<p>Open a new HTML project on Replit and add a <code>&lt;script&gt;</code> tag. Build a button that pops a greeting <strong>with your own name</strong> in it.</p>
<ol>
<li>Make a button on the page.</li>
<li>Write a function that runs when the button is clicked.</li>
<li>Inside the function, use <code>alert()</code> to say hello using your name.</li>
<li>Also send a message to the console with <code>console.log()</code> so you can see your code ran.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Stretch:</strong> add a second button with a <em>different</em> message — maybe your favorite food, or a fact about you.</p>
<p>When you finish, come back here. Send a <strong>photo or video</strong> of your page working, then explain what you did. Use these sentence starters — write 4 to 6 sentences total.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>First, I added a button that …</p>
<p>When the button is clicked, my function …</p>
<p>I used <code>alert()</code> to …</p>
<p>I used <code>console.log()</code> to …</p>
<p>One tricky moment was when …</p>
<p>If I had more time, I would …</p>
</blockquote>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>4 · Record Your Walkthrough 🎥</h2>
<p>Take a video on your phone (or a parent's phone) while your page runs. Talk through it like you are teaching someone who has never seen it. Try to use these words: <strong>button</strong>, <strong>function</strong>, <strong>click</strong>, <strong>alert</strong>, <strong>console</strong>.</p>
<blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Show your page before clicking anything.</li>
<li>Click the button and show the alert popping up.</li>
<li>Read your function out loud and say what makes it run.</li>
<li>Open the console and show your <code>console.log</code> message.</li>
</ol>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Write what you will say in your video.</strong> Plan it here before you record — you can read from it while filming.</p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h3>Submit ✅</h3>
<p>Send this worksheet + your walkthrough video to teacher on KakaoTalk.</p>
